  </para>
</solution>
</exercise><exercise id="eip-406"><problem id="eip-853">
  <para id="eip-361">
    The UTSA not only prohibits the actual disclosure or use of a trade secret, it also protects against the “threatened” disclosure of trade secrets. When might a court intervene to stop a “threatened” disclosure before the actual disclosure takes place?
<preformat id="eip-id1164449182159">
         A. An employee goes to work for another company in a different industry.
         B. An employee caught embezzling is fired and the employer believes the same lack of morals
             will lead to the fired employee disclosing trade secrets.
         C. An employee goes to work for an arch competitor in a comparable job position.
</preformat>
  </para>
</problem>

<solution id="eip-18">
